<h2>
    <a href="/blog/processing-uk-ordnance-survey-terrain-data/">Processing UK Ordnance Survey terrain data</a>
</h2>




<h6 class="post-meta">
    Posted by:
    
    <a href="/blog/author/christian/">christian</a>
    
    
    
    in
    
    <a href="/blog/category/featured-on-frontpage/">Featured on frontpage</a>
    
    
    
    on 10 Oct 2019
</h6>





<a href="/blog/processing-uk-ordnance-survey-terrain-data/">
    <img class="img-thumbnail pull-left" src="/static/media/uploads/blog/terrain50/.thumbnails/os-uk.png/os-uk-90x90.png">
</a>





<p>The UK's <a href="https://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/">Ordnance Survey</a> mapping agency now makes its 50 m resolution elevation data freely-available through its online <a href="https://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/opendatadownload/products.html#TERR50">OpenData download service</a>. This article uses Python, NumPy and Matplotlib to process and visualize these data without using a specialized GIS library.</p>




